					<p>The phrase =E2=80=9Clearning curve=E2=80=9D has become a common col=
loquial phrase to describe how a skill isn=E2=80=99t easily acquired. Typic=
ally, most learners experience a learning curve at the beginning of a new e=
xperience, and that incline tapers off as they gradually learn more about t=
he subject matter.</p>
<p>However, it=E2=80=99s more than just a common phrase. The learning curve=
 theory is a well-known concept still used today by learning and developmen=
t teams to drive knowledge retention and skill development. The learning cu=
rve mathematical formula provides organizations with a measurable way to un=
derstand how long it takes to acquire a skill or master a task. It may also=
 be described as the =E2=80=98experience curve=E2=80=99, =E2=80=98cost curv=
e=E2=80=99, =E2=80=98efficiency curve=E2=80=99, or =E2=80=98productivity cu=
rve=E2=80=99.</p>
<p>In this article, we=E2=80=99ll explore the Learning Curve Theory, its hi=
story, advantages and disadvantages, types of learning curves, how to calcu=
late it, and its application for modern <a href=3D"https://whatfix.com/blog=
/learning-development-strategy/">learning and development strategies</a>.</=
p>
<div class=3D"featured">
<span id=3D"elementor-toc__heading-anchor-0" class=3D"elementor-menu-anchor=
 "></span><span id=3D"elementor-toc__heading-anchor-0" class=3D"elementor-m=
enu-anchor "></span><h2>What Is a Learning Curve?</h2>
<p>The learning curve is the correlation between a learner=E2=80=99s perfor=
mance on a task or activity and the number of attempts or time required to =
complete the activity.</p>
</div>
<span id=3D"elementor-toc__heading-anchor-1" class=3D"elementor-menu-anchor=
 "></span><span id=3D"elementor-toc__heading-anchor-1" class=3D"elementor-m=
enu-anchor "></span><h2>Generalized vs. Measured Learning Curve</h2>
<p>The learning curve has both a general definition and a defined quantitat=
ive application.</p>
<ul>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><b>Generalized: </b>The ge=
neralized learning curve is a common phrase that describes the time it take=
s to learn a challenging task or skill. It can be a generalization, such as=
 learning how to ride a bike or become good at a specific video game, and i=
s a qualitative description of how long it takes to learn a skill.</li>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><b>Measured: </b>Measured =
learning curves are defined, and a mathematical formula calculates proficie=
ncy or expertise in a task. Skills must be repeatable and measurable to qua=
ntify, and one can only examine one variable in a skill, task, or process.<=
/li>
</ul>
<span id=3D"elementor-toc__heading-anchor-2" class=3D"elementor-menu-anchor=
 "></span><span id=3D"elementor-toc__heading-anchor-2" class=3D"elementor-m=
enu-anchor "></span><h2>History of the Learning Curve Theory</h2>
<p>The idea of the learning curve theory has been dated back to the 1880s a=
nd has evolved through the decades. Here is a brief overview of the learnin=
g curve model=E2=80=99s history:</p>
<h3>Ebbinghaus Forgetting Curve</h3>
<p>The idea of a learning curve was first proposed by Dr. Hermann Ebbinghau=
s in 1885 when developing his <a href=3D"https://whatfix.com/blog/ebbinghau=
s-forgetting-curve/">forgetting curve theory</a>. His theory was designed t=
o understand how people retain and lose information. It helps organizations=
 understand when and why we lose information and how we can fight this know=
ledge loss.</p>
<h3>General Experimental Psychology</h3>
<p>Fast-forward to 1934, Arthur Bills explores the idea of a learning curve=
 in his paper <a href=3D"https://archive.org/details/generalexperimen00bill=
/page/194/mode/2up"><i>General</i> <i>Experimental Psychology</i></a>, desc=
ribing it as a graphical representation of understanding efficiency improve=
ment rates on a given task or practice. Bills presented two types of learni=
ng curve graphs: one that represented an increase in productivity as time p=
rogressed and the second a declining curve showing the time needed to perfo=
rm a task.</p>
<h3>Wright=E2=80=99s Experience Curve</h3>
<p>In 1936, T.P. Wright developed the basis for the modern learning curve f=
ormula, which he termed the =E2=80=9CCumulative Average Model=E2=80=9D (als=
o known as =E2=80=9CWright=E2=80=99s Model=E2=80=9D) in his paper <a href=
=3D"http://www.uvm.edu/pdodds/research/papers/others/1936/wright1936a.pdf">=
<i>Factors Affecting the Cost of Airplanes</i></a>. Wright noted that the c=
ost of building airplanes decreased as production performance and efficienc=
y increased. While many variations of the learning curve model exist today,=
 this is the original formula=E2=80=99s foundation.</p>
<h3>Modern application for employee L&amp;D</h3>
<p>The learning curve theory is based on the concept that there is an initi=
al period where the amount invested in learners is more significant than th=
e return. However, after overcoming the learning curve, the return is much =
greater than the investment.</p>
<p>The idea here is that the more an employee practices a task, the better =
they become at it, which translates to a lower cost of training and higher =
output over time. The learning curve model helps track training progress, i=
mprove productivity, and predict learners=E2=80=99 performance and improvem=
ent over time.</p>
<span id=3D"elementor-toc__heading-anchor-3" class=3D"elementor-menu-anchor=
 "></span><span id=3D"elementor-toc__heading-anchor-3" class=3D"elementor-m=
enu-anchor "></span><h2>What=E2=80=99s the Learning Curve Formula?</h2>
<p>The original learning curve theory formula is: <b><i>Y =3D aX^b</i></b><=
/p>
<ul>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><b>Y</b> =3D The total ave=
rage time to perform the task per unit or batch</li>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><b>a</b> =3D Time taken to=
 perform task initially</li>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><b>X</b> =3D The total uni=
ts of production or times task completed.</li>
<li style=3D"font-weight: 400;" aria-level=3D"1"><b>b</b> =3D Represents th=
e learning curve function slope</li>
</ul>
<p>The learning curve is the correlation between a learner=E2=80=99s perfor=
mance on a task or activity and the number of attempts or time required to =
complete the activity.</p>
<p>The overall theory of the learning curve formula says that as the number=
 of times a person attempts a task increases, the overall amount of time to=
 complete the task will decrease. The learning curve formula can then predi=
ct how a person can learn a task.</p>
<p>However, the relationship between the time spent practicing an activity =
and overall performance is not linear. There will always be specific period=
s for each activity where a small amount of practice would yield massive ou=
tput improvement, or even minor improvements may require many work hours. T=
his variance in the relationship between training and proficiency over time=
 is known as the =E2=80=98learning curve.=E2=80=99</p>
